	<div class="5-star cf">
		<div class="review-author">
			<h4>By Dsmith</h4>
			From Norman OK<br />
			First-timer
		</div>
		<div class="review-content">
			<div class="score-small">
				<div class="star-on"><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
				<div class="star-on"><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
				<div class="star-on"><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
				<div class="star-on"><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
				<div class="star-on"><img src="data:image/png;base64," /></div>
			</div>
			<h2>Greatest thing ever</h2>
			<p>Let me first start out and say I think Weber makes the best grill for the money. I have had my Genesis e330 for almost 4 years and it still looks and performs like new. Weber designed this grill to last and I suspect I will get a solid ten years of use before I replace it. The construction is top notch and the materials are all first rate. I live in Michigan and even when its below zero or snowing I am out on my deck grilling. I use my Weber at least 3-4 times a week and grill a wide variety of meats, fish and chicken on this grill and it works great. 1 issue I have with this grill is the knobs on the face of the grill. You can too easily turn on each burner. You would think that this would be a good thing but if you use the Weber cover like I have the knobs can easily turn when you put the cover on, there bye turning on the gas and quickly loosing your tank. The cover for this grill is very snug so you better get used to turning off the valve to the tank before you put on the cover or you might accidently turn one of the burner knobs when putting on the cover and loosing your tank. It took me 3 lost tanks over a period of 6 months to finally figure out that I would need to turn the valve off before covering the grill. I know this sound like a petty issue but if you are spending $750 on a grill you would think the engineers designing this grill would have thought this part through. that being said I still love this grill and would recommend the grill even with the small flaw in design</p>
		</div>
	</div>

